<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06269297 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06269297 </ACCESS><DESCRIPT>  SPORT; BRIEF  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  When Santa Clara University applied to stage the NCAA's West Regionalbasketball playoffs in 1995, the real target year was 1997, Athletic DirectorTom O'Connor said Tuesday.;   After San Jose's 17,000-seat arena is completedin 1993, the West Coast Conference will join SCU in a bid for the '97 regionalor one of two sub-regionals, O'Connor said.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Sports  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  SAN JOSE AIMING FOR 1997 NCAA REGIONAL  </HEADLINE><MEMO>  Sports Digest; Mercury News Staff Writer John Akers contributed to this report.  </MEMO><TEXT>     Although the NCAA does not accept applications representing arenas that arenot completed, O'Connor said the reason last December's application was made&quot;was simply to get our name in the hopper. Also, we wanted people to knowabout our arena if someone had to pull out.&quot;;   Dean Munro, executive directorof the San Jose Sports Authority, said the NCAA would like to return to theBay Area. Oakland hosted the 1990 West Regional.;   O'Connor and SJS AthleticDirector Tom Brennan will meet Friday with the Sports Authority to discussbringing in big-name opponents such as Georgetown and Notre Dame to the arenafor the 1993-94 season.; TENNIS: Jimmy Connors, playing his first match sincea loss in the semifinals of the U.S. Open two weeks ago, beat Laurent Prades6-3, 6-1 in the opening round of the $750,000 Swiss indoor championships inBasel, Switzerland. . . . A team of area women will compete in the U.S. TennisAssociation league championship tournament starting Oct. 3 in Tucson, Ariz.Team members are Inky Amoroso and Andrea Okamura of Atherton, Carol Bottomlyof San Mateo, Claudia Giacomini of Sunnyvale, Linda Grosh and PriscillaHanrahan of Palo Alto, Karen Knowles of San Francisco, Shirley Marini of LosAltos Hills and Rebecca Snell of Menlo Park.; COLLEGES: After trailing for thefirst time this season, Stanford's ninth-ranked women's soccer team (6-0)rallied to score three goals in 3 minutes, 2 seconds in a 4-1 victory over St.Mary's (3-3) in Moraga.; PRO BASKETBALL: Oregon point guard Terrell Brandon,the 11th pick in the NBA draft, signed a seven-year contract with theCleveland Cavaliers. Under the league salary cap, Cleveland can pay Brandon$525,000 in his first year.; BOXING: Army Pfc. Anthony McWilliams of FortHuachuca, Ariz., died Friday of brain injuries suffered Sept. 3 whilesparring. He was 20. . . . Bantamweight Fernie Morales, 25, who underwentsurgery to remove a blood clot in his brain after losing a 12-round decisionSaturday, remained in critical condition in Indio. . . . Michael Watson, 26,injured in a Saturday bout in London, remained in critical condition asdoctors worked to reduce swelling of his brain. . . . Former heavyweightchampion Muhammad Ali, scheduled to make a series of appearances this week inEngland to promote sales of his biography, did not show up. Ali's wife,Lonnie, said Ali has been traveling in the Middle East and suggested hisabsence was due to pressure from Muslim associates who oppose the book.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Mercury News Staff and Wire Reports  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   910925  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Wednesday  </DAY><MONTH>  September  </MONTH><PG.COL>  10F  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  498  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Wednesday, September 25, 199100269297,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>